reviewText: Before I saw this movie I heard bad reviews for it. I thought the trailer was funny so I decided to see it. I'm glad I did! This movie is so funny!

Dont trust the bad reviews. The movie is so funny, my friends went to see it since it got worst movie of this year and at the end they love it. The movie is like someone says i am going to punch you, and you say okay. Then it hurts, and then you say, why did you punch me?

Okay, this film is definitely R-rated and ABSOLUTELY NOT "a family movie" or "for the little ones" in _any_ conceivable way.  But at times, this film composed of a series of shorts strung together by an appropriately flimsy master narrative is honestly very funny ;-)

A lot of people don't get it.  This movie is meant to be sick, it's meant to be offensive, it's meant to be in bad taste.  The novelty here is that there are big stars in all the roles.  I won't give away any of it, only to say that if you like sketch comedies in the tradition of The Groove Tube, Kentucky Fried Movie and Amazon Women On The Moon, you owe it to yourself to check this one out.  And for those of you who think yourself "above" the material, get over yourselves already.

I hear about this movie & that it was getting a lot of negative feedback. I became very curious to see how bad it was......and boy oh boy I wish I never saw this movie at all. This movie is horrible & I really don't know where to start. Okay, the movie is a series of short films with a wraparound starting Dennis Quaid (Dress up like Justin Bieber) playing a screenwriter trying to pitch these ideas to a film executive, played by Greg Kinnear. Each short is really NOT that funny. I did chuckled a few times, but never laugh out loud. I feel unclean after watching it & I know it's a comedy. I know it's supposed be crude, shocking, gross, disgusting, tasteless & offensive. But it didn't work for me. If you liked it than good for you, because I sure didn't. I'm gonna said this right now to you: DON'T GO SEE THIS MOVIE! It is the lowest forms of humor. This is the bottom of the barrel of comedy. The whole cast & crew who made this terrible movie needs to be ashamed of themselves. All of the actors in this film look like they collect their checks before even reading the script or not at all. You know what this reminds me of. A comedy called, "The Kentucky Fried Movie". A really funny & enjoyable film. It's has all the elements like this one, but it's done better. Go see that movie instead of this turkey.

Outside Magnolia, this has to be the most bizarre thing Ive ever seen.  Everybody and everything - including the Holocaust - is fair game here, and some of it is uproariously funny.  Unfortunately, though, most of it is just plain weird.  I spent most of the movie marveling at how the producers were able to convince so many a-list stars to appear in this.  I think the movie is supposed to be stupid, but whats the point of making a movie thats supposed to be stupid?  If you're looking for reasons to be offended, you won't have to look far here.  I wasn't offended by any of it, but I would never be tempted to watch it again.

To be honest, I would rate it at 4 stars but I have to try to offset all of the single stars so that this gem (in the rough, to be sure) does not go unnoticed. I rarely write reviews but, since their purpose is to provide descriptive commentary of a product (as well as personal opinions), I felt the need to do so here because I think that the description provided is not sufficient and will cause some viewers to be offended. That is to say, this movie is not for everyone. And, while the meager description may add to the shock value of the movie, it will likely only serve to decrease the movie's rating in an unfair (or undesired, at least) manner.

I think that the content this movie was created (or inspired) by some collection of actors who were losing their minds with the spoon-fed crapola that permeates the mainstream film industry and just wanted to loosen their collars a bit. It could (and maybe should, to be honest) be legitimately described as offensive, but not in an offending manner. This movie is obviously not for young ones.

This is a collection of short stories (sort of). Funny short stories. Funny short stories with uncommon subject matter. Thats all I have to say about that. I certainly wouldnt want to ruin it for you. To say that this movie is pointless and has only comedic value is an insult, regardless of the judge. Its message is not subtle but still might be hard to hear over the deafening roar of the material.

This isn't a movie for sissies. It is definitely a comedy and is awesomely funny.

However, if you consider yourself a spiritual person, you will hate it. If you consider yourself a mature person, you will hate it. If you consider yourself a person with sophistication, you will hate it. If you . . Well, you get the idea. If not, let me put it this way: if you take comfort by living in a secure and proper fashion, it is likely that this movie will reach down, bite you in the ass and use your face to smash down the boundaries of your sensibilities and it won't be pretty.

If you are the type of person I described above, please do yourself and others a favor and give this movie a pass (just look at all of the 1-star ratings). There is nothing wrong in you being who you are, but if you are as such and you watch this then you will likely feel the need to waste your (and others) time by writing a hateful rail against the villainous content of this film and your wasted money and your wasted two hours, etc. Dont go away mad, just go away. Youve been warned.

If you decide to take the plunge, just relax and let it do its thing. If you are uptight in the least then this film will own you.

Honestly I have no idea why this movie gets such bad reviews from so many people.  Yes, it's stupid, stupid comedy but you know that going in - especially if you buy the DVD.  The skits are hilarious and a big part of the humor is the fact that they got this huge actors to do such crazy skits.  We've laughed so hard at this movie several times and I'm glad we own it because we've got a lot more laughs watching in the future coming our way.

Movie 43 is basically a skit show as a movie based around the fact that Denis Quaid's character is trying to sell his movie to a studio and coming up with each storyline, mostly at gunpoint since it's obvious no one would actually make this thing.  A lot of the skits are heavy on the crude humour, most you'll get a few laughs from, some aren't funny at all (the basketball room, the homeschooled one)  and some them you got over the joke before they moved onto something else (Hugh Jackman something hanging from his chin scene).  None are so brilliant that you'll be telling anyone you have to see this to see this scene, and reviewing this the next day I struggle to even remember some of them.  But some of the highlights for me was Justin Long as Robin (from 1966 TV era Batman and Robin) on a speed dating night when Batman (Jason Sudeikis) turns up and becomes an annoying third wheel ruining his chances with the ladies (also has Kristen Bell in it as Supergirl).  Chloe Moretz on a young teen come over to her boyfriend's house and make out for the first time who gets her period while sitting on the couch and the date and his older brother freak out and dial 911 where the operator laughs at them.  The Tampax commercial after this was so ridiculous it was hysterical.  As were some of the other commercials like raising awareness of kids in the machines, and the iBabe hazard.

But there's plenty of big stars in this one, besides those already mentioned there's Anna Farris, Emma Stone, Kate Bosworth,  Gerard Butler, Halle Berry, Elizabeth Banks, Josh Duhamel, Richard Gere, amongst many others. It's worth watching once and it if it didn't have the big names it probably wouldn't have worked but it's not something you're likely to watch a second time.  Three and half stars.

I was shocked to see this briefly pop up in Amazon's recommended list of movies on my page. I didn't watch it on Amazon - I had rented it from Redbox and it was the worst piece of crap I ever had watched.  What does Amazon do when deciding to recommend movies?  See if you've watched a similar genre and then put movies of the genre with big names in it into a hat and pull them out randomly?  The recommendation was on my page only briefly, when I looked again, it was gone.
It's a wonder as to why they would have even dared to recommend a movie that many have described as the worst movie ever made.  Ratings from IMDb (2 of 5 stars),  Rotten Tomatoes (4%), and Metacritic (18%) are all very low.  Audience score for Rotten Tomatoes was only 24% of people who liked it.  This movie should never pop up on a 'recommended" list for anyone, it is just that bad.  I am sure there are a few who liked it,  but the amount of people who did not is astronomical.  So why would Amazon take the chance?  I've started to watch a few bad movies on it,  but never finished them and none have even come near to being as much of a failure as Movie 43.

Not for those with a weak stomach, this movie is actually well crafted.  It teases the viewer by treading a thin line between discomfort and outright disgust.  It made me squirm the way Ricky Gervais did in his role as boss in the UK version of The Office. It was hard to watch and yet I couldn't quite stop, either.

 The absurdity of the plots and dialogue illustrate bigoted social norms we usually don't question, in a way that felt similar to watching Borat.  It's biting satire dressed up as low brow comedy.

A lot of promise in this concept, but this film falls flat. It's one of the lease enjoyable films I've seen in a long time. While there are some good shorts in this film, the overall film drags them down too much. So disappointed.

Whats it about?

A mind-boggling list of Hollywood actors star in a series of loosely connected shorts joined together by The Pitch, in which Dennis Quaid plays an unpredictable lunatic aggressively trying to sell his awful script to embattled studio exec Greg Kinnear (easily the most relatable character in the film).

What did I think?

A class of illiterate orphans with four broken pencils, three sheets of paper and a reference copy of Das Kapital could write a funnier movie than this, and there would probably be fewer dick jokes. If you ever feel like your life has no purpose, now you know it does: to go and punch Peter Farrelly right in his stupid face.

I'm a cranky 48-year-old who doesn't dig most recent attempts at absurd comedy. {For the record, I absolutely love "Monty Python," SNL, and "South Park," especially the early seasons.} I was in a particularly crabby mood when I started watching MOVIE 43 and almost stopped it after the early "ballsy blind date" skit, but something bade me to stay with it, and even though I wasn't all that satisfied, it cheered me up and even made me lol, something I don't often do, in a couple of spots.

There is some nice satire and parody here on a bunch of miscellaneous subjects: home schooling, computer dating sites, breast enlargement surgery, superheroes, after-school specials, you name it. The fact that there are so many Hollywood big-shots in parodies of their typical roles adds a great deal to this little batch of spoofs. There's a lot of gross humor, of course: Scat, mutilation, body parts, etc, but to my pleasant surprise, MOVIE 43 doesn't feel the need to just rub its audience's face in these elements, making its point without showing TOO much nauseating stuff. {Fans of nauseating stuff will definitely find some here, but they may be disappointed that it doesn't go farther.}

The biggest problem is that it's nowhere near as developed and focused as it could be, and virtually all the scenes, many of which would be worth entire films unto themselves, end just as they start to get interesting. But maybe that's the point because, as the young aspiring filmmakers in the central story attest, the biggest thing this film seems to be parodying is today's lazily produced low budget films (premature credits rolling at 76 minutes, etc).

Though it's far from great, there are definitely some things to appreciate here. MOVIE 43 is disorganized and underdone, but even in those respects, it still works (kind of). I think that 25 or so years ago, when I was more into humor for its own sake and less inclined to analyze everything to death, my verdict would have been the same.

Maybe it's a generational thing, but at my age I still have a fondness for slapstick comedy. This film feeds that with the addition of wildly "shocking" story lines with the crudest of crude themes. That's what it's designed to do! Obviously, the producers never expected to win at Cannes or have the Academy envelope opened in their favor, but they do successfully target an audience willing and desirous of cutting the apron strings of convention, but not in the direction of zombie and action hero movies that swamp the circuit these days.

That said, "Movie 43" isn't funny throughout, like that other slapstick jewel, "Airplane!". But its few low spots have nothing to do with backing away from its reliance on grotesque themes, but rather some plotting and acting deficiencies. Those are few and far between, however, and overall I give this film three thumbs up! (How three, you ask? Well, if Hugh Jackman can have his balls hanging from his neck, what's so odd about having three thumbs?)

First thing, I am NOT a fan of potty and profanity type humour. That's why this movie really suprised me. It's got a great cast and is suprisingly well directed. Yes, it's crude, very crude, with themes of the afore mentioned potty humour and profanity, as well as sex, violence, periods, and a whole bunch of other stuff. However, behind all that, it is actually well written in parts. My favourites being the sketch where the girl from Kick Ass (the main one) is around her boyfriends house and she tries to get away or at least hide the fact that she just had her first period. She then gets surrounded by various male characters (her boyfriend, boyfriend's older brother, boyfriend's dad and her dad) who haven't a clue what to do and try to help her in a sterotypically male way, which makes for some good laughs and highlights the sterotype of how males don't have a clue about periods. Another good one is the last one with Elizabeth Banks and the rivalry she has with her boyfriend's male cat, for the boyfriend's affections. The cat itself is a cartoon, quite literally. Sick and strange but still funny with a deliciously dark ending. The blind date one with Halle Berry and the co-writer of the British version of the Office (not Ricky Gervais) gets pretty crazy but still amusing as they get each other to do outlandish dares.

Overall, yes it's extreme and the gags and themes are crudely out there. If you get easily offended by anything I have mentioned, avoid this. If you like Jackass, Seth Mcfarlane stuff, Farrely Brothers (Peter Farrely- Something about Mary, co-made this), crude stand up comics and dark humour (like in Kick Ass), with a bit of Kevin Smith thrown in, think you'll like it. Yes, there are some bad sketches amongst the better ones and it would have been a better movie if it was a little less Seth Mcfarlane and more Kevin Smith, but it isn't. Still, it's good for a few laughs, and if like me, you generally don't like potty humour but enjoy gags that sterotype people, dark humour, satire, observational comedy and don't mind swearing, then give it a go, because some of the writing is defintitely clever. I think the level of grossness in this, clouds the fact that it does contain some clever writing, at least for the better sketches. I guess it is possible to be clever and disgusting. Just don't watch it with kids or easily offended people. Also, it's definitely a 'guys' type of movie and does sexualize women too much.

This movie was hilarious! I'd never heard of it until a friend of mine suggested we watch it. The concept is brilliant - a guy is pitching a bunch of movie ideas to a studio executive and as he is pitching an idea, you are watching the idea, and as soon as you get that feeling that you are "done" with that skit, it's over. So you end up with multiple hilarious movie "ideas" to watch with no awkward dead air waiting for the movie to hurry up.
With a normal comedy, you always still have a "story line" - whether it be a love story or something, and there are usually downer moments somewhere in there that I always find myself looking at my watch, wanting it to hurry up and get funny again.
This movie isn't Oscar worthy by any means. It's just a bunch of funny movie "skits" or "short films" made to make you laugh the entire time.
All I can say is ummm, well, ya see, hmmmm, I don't even know where to begin.  Dirty humor, not funny humor, decent humor.  It is an ensemble comedy.

This is great movie set in the theme of 70's greats Tunnelvision and Kentucky Fried Movie etc. If you like outrageous skits with a little more time than TV like Saturday Night Live have to devote you will laugh so hard you cry.

Those who don' "get it" are really just too up tight.  The difference between those movies this emulates and this one is many really great comedians came "out" of and helped write them early in their careers, here very "serious" actors are allowed to do something daring after becoming famous and recognized.

[Forgive me if I misspell some of the performers names.]

Dennis Quaid is a crazed author of a series of skits (and commercials for some reason) he is pushing (forcefully) to Greg Kinnear, a film mogul. This is the thread that runs throughout the entire film as a base theme. I was bowled-over by the cast of this film. I didn't know much about it until I saw it, but I enjoyed much of it. There are definitely parts that fall flat or even a bit lower, but more than 1/2 the film is so outrageous and over-the-top that it's damn funny. The writers definitely went for the sicko concepts, most of which they couldn't get on TV today, despite Seth MacFarlane, the king of bizarre/offensive humor being in the film as himself.

Hugh Jackman on a blind date with a beautiful woman in a fancy restaurant has a normal-sized scrotum growing under his chin. The poor woman tries to be cool, but it's pretty hard. That was a funny sketch.

There's a sketch about what could happen if home schooling were taken to the extreme that's pretty funny.

The skit with Hali Berri is weird funny. She and her date do some unthinkable things to themselves when they engage in a serious game of Truth or Dare.

These three sketches along with some of the segments that return to Quaid's increasingly forceful (guns and gernade anyone?) attempts to sell his script are the highlights of the film for me.

The late "Tony Soprano" makes a cameo as a security guard Dennis Quaid had to "blow" (against the guard's will no less) to get on the movie lot in the first place.

The fake commercials and final sketch about a black basketball team afraid to play their first white opponents have a few chuckles but don't really work very well.

This film has been compared to "Kentucky Fried Movie," a disconnected string of comedy sketches done in, I believe, the early 1980s, but this film is MUCH more amusing than "Kentucky Fried Movie," which contains only about 10 minutes of really funny material.

If you have a really twisted sense of humor like I do, you'll enjoy this movie despite its shortcomings. It's crass, gross and is rarely "tasteful" in the least. If that sounds like fun to you, give this film a try. There are parts you will definitely want to share with your friends as they won't believe you without proof. If you are more reserved in your taste, you might want to pass on this one.

Instead of my usual listing of who is directing, writing and staring in it, I realize that it would take too much space and time to do so. I actually attempted to write a review of this.....thing I am supposed to call a film, but I thought it would be take too much time from actually writing my opinion on the film. So, to those who wish to know who had their involvement in this film, go to Wikipedia, IMDB or any similar website that provides film information. As for the film itself.....where, oh where to begin?

Movie 43 began its small, pitiful life as an idea from one of its producers, Charles B. Wessler. Wessler's work is more well known as a right hand man of sorts to the Farrelly Brothers, the one-hit wonders behind such works such as There's Something About Marry and Kingpin. It was to be an all ensemble cast of the funniest minds in Hollywood of writers, directors, actors and actresses, all being incredibly silly and funny. The project kept on going through all sorts of development troubles, with it being constantly started up, then stopped and so on and so forth. Eventually, the film was able to finally see the light of day in early 2013, released during a time when pretty much nothing is coming out (e.g. January) and how did the film do? Well, it made money (29 million world wide on a 6 million dollar budget), but as evidenced by films like Transformers Revenge of The Fallen and The Devil Inside, just because it made money doesn't mean its good.

Thanks to Movie 43, we can now say that films with all star casts are no long a surefire thing that the film is of any excellent quality. Now, to summarize the plot of Movie 43 can be somewhat of an exercise in futility, but I shall do the best I can. There are two different versions of the film that exist, with a different segment that ties all of these together, so I shall go with the one I had seen. Charlie Wessler (Dennis Quaid) is attempting to greenlight multiple script ideas to film producer Griffin Schraeder (Greg Kinneer). Wessler even resorts to threatening others at gun point to get his ideas off the ground. The film shows us Wessler's harebrained ideas on screen which include the following:

- A segment in which Kate Winslet goes a on a blind date with Hugh Jackman who has a pair of testicles on his neck.

- Two parents, played by actual couple Liev Screiber and Naomi Watts, decide to homeschool their son, played by Jeremy Allen White, while also putting him through all the humiliating things a kid might experience during high school.

- Johnny Knoxville decides to get his best friend, played by Sean William Scott, a Leprechaun played by Gerard Butler for his birthday in an attempt to get his gold. Gratuitous violence and swearing ensues.

- Justin Long plays Robin from the DC Comics, who goes on speed dating with the help of Batman, played by Jason Sudeikis.

- Anna Faris is going on a date with Chris Pratt and to celebrate their relationship, she wants Pratt to s***
 on her. Pratt's character then eats a grotesque amount of stomach rupturing food to do so.

And so on and so forth.

Now, I have seen some utterly revolting works in my time, both in the positive sense and negative. Stuff that most mainstream audiences would shun away from that select audiences and I would get massive enjoyment from. On the positive sense, I've sat through the works of directors like Lars von Trier, Takashi Miike, Park Chain Wook, Darren Aronofsky - Directors who push the boundaries of filmmaking that can both make the audience cringe to hell and back while challenging the way think and see film. On the negative sense, I've sat through the bottom of the barrel when it comes to filmmaking such as the works of Jason Friedberg And Aaron Seltzer, some of the works from Michael Bay and Uwe Boll. But even all of those filmmakers I just listed, even the bad ones, would be possibly terrified by what has been put on display here.

The film apparently runs 94 minutes over here in the States, but what  should have felt like a quick and painless routine became more or less an eternity, like being thrown into a black hole that traveled at an incredibly slow rate whilst taking a lot of psychoactive drugs. Every single segment that would constantly be thrown at me wasn't in singular sense funny, amusing, creative or even off the track. Instead, they were lazy, stupid, unfunny, poorly paced, insulting and any and every single word from any kind of dictionary, whether it'd be in English or whatever kind of foreign language out there.

 All of the film's participants make absolute fools of themselves in this film and not in a funny way. For example, the aforementioned part when Wolverine has balls on his neck? The entire gag comes off as someone going like "TEE HEE HEE HEE! LOOK! HE'S GOT BALLS ON HIS NECK! NO ONE ISN'T NOTICING IT EXCEPT FOR HIS DATE! HIS PUBES JUST DROPPED INTO HIS SOUP! ISN'T THAT FUNNY?" Yeah, it'd be funny if there was more jokes surrounding it outside of an insipid gag that goes on for far too long. There's also the "Poop" segment I mentioned, in which when it hits its gastric crescendo, has this utterly ugly and mean spirited vibe to it. You feel absolutely dirty watching the damn thing.

Hell, even from the stills or watching a trailer, you can tell that this film was cheap to make. Everything has this slightly icky feel to them when watching, like the camera they were using was something you'd get at a cheap ass garage sale than a Hollywood production. I have seen films that cost less that what Movie 43 did that look much more polished and have more effort in them than what this Hollywood infested pierce of garbage looks like. A film like Moon, which costed 1 million less than this, has utterly stunning effects, set and costume design and a bunch creativity behind it. This, on the other hand, does not have ANY of these qualities what so ever!

For those who will probably say to me that I don't "Have a sense of humor" or "Not every film is 2001", allow me to say this in response: For starters, I never bothered to watch the rest of 2001. I liked what I saw, but I never bothered to get around to it. Secondly, I have enjoyed really dumb comedies before. The Razzie Award winning Freddy Got Fingered, co-written, directed and starring Tom Green, is utterly repulsive by regular standards but I find it to be quite creative and strangely amusing. There is some genuine creativity behind the film, such as the film infamous "Daddy Would You Like Some Sausage" part, in which Tom Green constructs a system to play the piano while eating Sausages tied up on a series of strings. But there isn't a scene in Movie 43 that made me feel this way.

Admittedly, I do have a degree of sympathy for those who participated in the film. Apparently, a lot of the cast was just pretty much suckered into the picture, guilt tripped or outright manipulated by the film's producers. For example, Richard Gere did not want to be in his sketch in which he runs an Apple-like corporation that sells i-pods in the shape of fully grown naked Women. He said he couldn't come to the set, so the filmmakers brought the set to him. Other actors and directors also got a chance to get out of this mess, such as Sam Rockwell, who choose Seven Psychopaths over this or George Clooney, who pretty much told them "No f***ing way".

I'm not the kind of person who goes out of their to insult others because of their taste in film or anything in terms of art or media. It is a pet peeve of mine, ever since I saw Bob "Moviebob" Chipman from The Escapist act like a childish brat over people seeing The Expendables over Scott Pilgrim vs The World. It's not a good character trait and can make you look like an ass. But, as much as I hate saying this and I will not take back what I have said, I must confess: If you think films like Man of Steel, Star Trek Into Darkness or any other big-budget, over-the top, over produced blockbuster is the worse thing you've seen this year without haven't seen this or some kind of insult to cinema, I only have one thing to say:

You have no spine. You wouldn't know a bad movie if it came along and presented itself in all of its vacuous glory. You should be lucky to watch anything instead of this. Movie 43 is the epitome of utterly vacuous, disgusting and tasteless filmmaking. It is the worst film of this year, the worst film of this young decade so far and easily one of the worst films ever conceived by the Hollywood system.

Is critically panned "Movie 43" really that bad? I think it is although I must add that I have seen much worse "comedies" than this before, something abysmally bad like Jason Friedberg & Aaron Seltzer's "Disaster Movie" made about five years ago.

The most impressive part "Movie 43" is the casting. The film boasts an outstanding cast of stars including: Kristen Bell, Halle Berry, Kate Bosworth, Kieran Culkin, Josh Duhamel, Anna Faris (with her real-life husband Chris Pratt), Terrence Howard, Hugh Jackman, Johnny Knoxville, Justin Long, Christopher Mintz-Plasse, Chlo Grace Moretz, Richard Gere, Jason Sudeikis, Liev Schreiber (with his real-life partner Naomi Watts), Seann William Scott, Emma Stone, Uma Thurman, Patrick Warburton and Kate Winslet! Plus, Greg Kinnear, Seth MacFarlane and Dennis Quaid (only in American version)! Oh, and I almost forgot Gerard Butler as leprechaun.

"Movie 43" is a series of loosely connected comedy skits in the vein of very influential comedy "The Kentucky Fried Movie," with each segment directed by such people as Elizabeth Banks (who also appears), Steven Brill, Griffin Dunne, Peter Farrelly, James Gunn and Brett Ratner.

You may laugh a few times or perhaps more, but as a whole the film is just a mess. The sporadically funny film's only selling point is that these talented stars are doing jokes that are most inappropriate. Actually, that those jokes are mostly crude, sexual, scatological, and offensive does not matter. The problem with the film is that they come up with a silly joke and stretches it too far.

"Movie 43" sets out to be a raunchy, gross-out comedy with A-list actors, but quickly becomes tiresome because of sloppy direction and one-joke ideas that go nowhere.

My guess is that a bunch of Hollywood A-listers did this project for 2 reasons: to have fun and blow off some steam.  The film centers around the outrageous ideas and antics of a pushy, desperate, bad writer who's trying to sell his stories to a big Hollywood exec.  Actors and producers are constantly having to filter through bad writing, which must be frustrating  The film shows that no matter how good an actor is, no matter how great the performance, if its a bad script the final product will be ridiculous-which the movie is, but in a funny way.  They certainly saved the best for last with the short Halle Berry's in-LMAO!

These unconnected skits are each based on a joke, a premise, that is barely funny and then the bit goes on for way agonizing minutes--it's like a blue version of Saturday Night Live at its very worst.

This first skit's premise is rip of a joke from the animated TV show "South Park" but done without the context, story, and characterizations -- whatever you think of South Park, this is a hundred times less funny. Plus the skit goes on for many minutes. The first skit's joke is basically "I can't stop staring at his mole" but a blue version. What possibly might have worked in some contexts for couple of seconds as a throwaway joke is worse than boring stretched over a skit of several minutes. And then the movie continued with one such bad poorly written, poorly timed skit after another.

The film has a good array of actors--so blame the writers and director. As an alternative to the buying/renting this film, throw some money on the waste basket and then go stare at a wall for an hour and a half. It will be funnier.

Were the producers double or triple dog dared to make the most offensive film ever to see if a big name cast could still sell it? Well, judging from the number of people, including me, who fell for it, that may have been the strategy. I guess that's why they didn't let the critics see it first. Thank goodness I watched it on Amazon and didn't pay for a theater ticket.

I realize that humor is largely in the mind of the beholder. South Park, Team America, Amazon Women on the Moon, anything featuring Sacha Baron Cohen - I find them all pretty funny and even clever in spots in spite of their utter tastelessness and the fact that I also find parts of them offensive. But Movie 43 has no redeeming qualities whatsoever. It isn't even mildly amusing, unless you're stuck at the mental age where anything dealing with poop and/or genitalia is automatically hilarious. And if you're really at that age, your parents shouldn't have this movie in the house.

I'm used to having my intelligence insulted by Hollywood, but this is way beyond the pale. No wonder the studios are going broke.

I'm not quite sure how they pulled it off, but the makers of "Movie 43" have somehow managed to rope some of the biggest names in Hollywood (their identities will be withheld to protect the guilty) into appearing in a comedy that hits a new low in witlessness, offensiveness and tastelessness. Did none of these fine actors read the script - or at least have agents to do it for them and thus warn them off the project? As it is, I suspect most of these performers will be working overtime trying to expunge this jaw-droppingly awful cinematic turkey from their resumes. I can only imagine that a goodly number of people in Hollywood must have lost careers and jobs over this one.

The movie is really just a series of blackout sketches (a la "Saturday Night Live"), all written and directed by different artists, held together by the flimsiest of narrative devices: Dennis Quaid plays a gun-wielding, mentally unbalanced screenwriter who invades the office of a studio exec (Greg Kinnear) and proceeds to pitch an idea for a movie that he's convinced will be a bona fide box office bonanza. The labored segments cover such topics as genitalia, scatology, incest - you name it, it's in there. Look, I like dirty jokes and gross-out humor as much as the next fella', but when each attempt lands with a resounding thud, all that's left is the gross-out and the dirty - and you'll probably feel the need for a shower after it's over.

How this much talent could be responsible for this much dreck is indeed a question for the ages.

"Movie 43" looked so promising, with a massive star-filled cast; I was hoping for an updated "Kentucky Fried Movie."  It ended up more of a turkey, unfortunately.  I knew that the movie had received terrible ratings, but as a huge fan of Kate Winslet (as well as a few of the other stars, including Naomi, Watts, Emma Stone, Chris Pratt, and Kieran Culkin), I still had to see this movie.

The movie is divided into 10 skits, 3 commercials, and a wrap-around skit that tries to tie everything together.  The wrap-around stars Greg Kinnear as a movie executive and Dennis Quaid (who looks extremely leathery here) as a producer trying to pitch picture ideas.  The "ideas" are the skits, although most of them make no sense as actual movies, and how the commercials fit into this concept is never explained.  A few of the skits elicit chuckles; however, most of them completely bomb and/or are jaw-droppingly raunchy.  I have nothing against raunchiness, but it has to be funny.

The movie starts off fine with the first skit, featuring Kate Winslet and Hugh Jackman on a blind date.  Kate cannot figure out why the dazzling Hugh is still single, until he reveals a bizarre disfigurement.  Apparently, this skit was the first one made and subsequently was used to entice other stars to join in the picture.  If they had continued at this level of quality then the movie may have been a 3-star affair, but it quickly devolves with the scatologically-obsessed "The Proposition," which stars real-life couple Anna Farris and Chris Pratt.  They are two of the most likeable stars out there, and the skit does have a few funny lines, but like so many of the other sketches it quickly overstays its welcome and becomes simply disgusting.  The same thing applies to the appalling animated section, "Beezel," about an obscenely disturbing cat.

Despite the negative reviews, many people are likely to be curious about this movie and want to see one of their favorite stars.  I too got suckered into seeing this exceptionally bad movie.  Fortunately, it's short and the brevity of most of the skits make it go by quickly.
Please DO NOT waste your money on this movie!! This was not funny at all and I really wish I could get my $4.99 back!!

NOT: a lot of things and not for everybody, that's for sure.
It is well-made and well-acted.
This would be a mistake for a lot of people as a shared diversion.
"Awkward" it is, even for a person viewing it alone as I was.
BUT this movie is one that had me really laughing.
Bizarre is an apt description.
One sketch of several did nothing for me and made me wonder "what happened here?". Filler at the end?
I'm a bachelor so if that tells something about who might enjoy it, well...
I also loved Kentucky Fried Movie, Airplane, some of The Groove Tube, The Meaning of Life(and the rest), early Woody Allen, and so on typical stuff for a guy born in '61. These were all "better" in their time, but still classics.
Movie43 is not a family film, not really a date film(maybe!), and does not wield any obvious political agenda(refreshing).

Saw Movie 43 in the cinema. I can't remember the last time I laughed so hard. It is really a masterpiece of its genre. Not for everyone, of course. You have to loosen up and go along for the ride. It has a stellar cast and just to see them do the things they do is worth the price of two tickets, 2 drinks, and 2 large popcorns. The sketches aren't all funny, of course. Different sketches will appeal to--or disgust--different people. I think the cast and the filmmakers really deserve applause for taking it "there".

I have no idea what those that gave this a poor review were thinking. This movie is extremely offensive. But no more so than anything Seth MacFarlane has ever done. Very funny, well written, well acted. Oh, and if you were surprised by the movie after watching the preview, you're an imbecile. The preview gave us a pretty good idea on what the movie was like. And there you go.
With all the talent who were in the movie, I could not honestly believe how horrible it was.  It is the absolute worst movie of ALL time!

The commercial made out Movie 43 to be an all around laugh, and almost makes it seem like the movie will be a cohesive story. Not so. It's a bunch of small stories trying to fit in this grand scheme for a movie pitch. But none of the stories have anything to do with each other. It reminds me of SNL, because the storyline of the "movie" seems like a bunch of sketches (some kinda good, some kinda really awful). Some of the movie was crude, but I usually like that sort of humor. However, Movie 43 crosses even some of my boundaries, and I'm not sure how you may feel about some of that humor. Some of the movie was downright uncomfortable and I was waiting for it to get better. SPOILER: It never did.

This morning I borrowed MOVIE 43 (2012) from a REDBOX kiosk and was looking forward to seeing it, until just now, when I checked it out at IMDb. A low rating (4.4) wasn't immediately discouraging, for I often disagree with IMDb voters on a picture's worth. Their synopsis: "A series of interconnected short films follows a washed-up producer as he pitches insane story lines featuring some of the biggest stars in Hollywood." There are 11 directors and 16 producers involved with this opus. The only one I'm familiar with, Bob Odenkirk, co-hosted the HBO sketch comedy series, MR. SHOW. The cast list of MOVIE 43 includes Dennis Quaid, Greg Kinnear, Hugh Jackman, Kate Winslet, Liev Schreiber, Naomi Watts, Kieran Culkin, Richard Gere, Emma Stone, Kate Bosworth, Uma Thurman, Patrick Warburton, Halle Berry, Tony Shaloub (uncredited) and an incredibly huge number of others. Seems promising, but then.... After reading several reviews I see now why it's so low rated: the film is merely a bunch of scatological scenarios, one more gross than the other. It's the sort of picture you either love, perhaps because you were stoned when watching it, or hate, because the film is meant to offend the sensibilities and succeeds. Well, I wasn't high when "43" ran on my laptop PC and I do have my standards. Yes there's parts that made me cringe, but I definitely laughed at others, so I'm right in the middle on it. PS-- remember: don't stick anything in iBabe that you're not willing to lose.

I'm just not sure how they blackmailed them to be in this movie and do what they did; otherwise appearing in something like this would be a potential career killer for an actor.

Probably worth a rent if you enjoy this kind of humor.  3 stars because some of the shorts in here aren't that funny (to me); and the fact that this probably shouldn't be compiled into a movie you pay money for. If I could give Movie 43 negative stars, I would. And I haven't even seen it. You don't have to see a movie to know that it is bad. Worse then bad, actually.

In the words of critics: "Take the nastiest, least-funny Saturday Night Live skit that's ever been produced, then add hundreds of profanities, bestiality, incest, testicles, bullying, full-frontal nudity, homophobic slurs, excrement fetishes, penis tattoos, prosthetic breasts dipped in guacamole..." and "Movie 43 is the Citizen Kane of awful" and "Being punched in the face was easier that watching this movie" and "Absolutely disgusting, nauseating, misogynistic, racist, cruel, void of any common sense..." and "Be afraid. Be very afraid."

If I could round-up every copy of this trash, bury it in the depths of the earth for a thousand thousand years, exhume it, burn what's left, extinguish the flames with Tabasco sauce, reignite the ashes, pound the remains of it into fine powder with a hammer, and gather up that powder and blow it into the northern wind, I would.

I seriously do not know how so many legitimate actors and actresses were roped into this travesty. Here is the only plausible theory that me, 43 NASA scientists, and a supercomputer came up with:

Hugh Jackman's house was invaded, and his family was held at gunpoint to force him to do the film. Liev Schrieber, Naomi Watts, and Kate Winslet were sent fake scripts, and held hostage at gunpoint to prevent them from escaping from the film set. Emma Stone, Gerard Butler, and Chloe Grace Moretz were heavily drugged. Dennis Quaid was under hypnotic influence, as was Uma Thurman. Halle Berry was told to do the film or they would make a sequel to Catwoman. Faced with an impossible choice, she did what anyone would do. Movie 43 makes Catwoman look like The Dark Knight. Christopher Mintze-Plasse, Anna Faris, and Terrence Howard were blackmailed.

That is all I can come up with. This trash has no redeeming factors. None at all.
It is unfunny, stupid, filthy, disgusting, perverted garbage.

As for thumbs, I would consider going under surgery involving a prototype genetically-modified super serum to grow more thumbs just so I could rate this film lower.

Okay, here's where things get really weird; I actually, sort of, liked MOVIE 43.  At least, the "version" I saw.  If you've seen 'Kentucky Fried Movie', and liked it, this is a hyped-up, jacked-on-crack, 2013 version of the same film - or, more accurately, a series of short (sometimes very short), interconnected and usually unrelated short films, with a wraparound story interspersed in between them to try and hold the "storyline" (of which there really isn't one) together.

For the American release, the wraparound story is "The Pitch", where a down-and-out film producer (Dennis Quaid) tries to pitch his crazy-assed movie idea to a studio head (Greg Kinnear).  This is NOT the version I saw (from what I've read, I caught the version that was released internationally), and I'm sort of glad because the wraparound story on the version I saw - about three geeks, two of whom trick the third into looking for the mysterious (even deadly) 'Movie 43' online - was fairly hilarious, and seemed to fit the idea of why there were a bunch of short films looped together in a more logical way.

The shorts themselves, good GOD what a cast!  Throughout the film you will see no less than Kate Winslet, Hugh Jackman, Halle Berry, Anna Faris, Chris Pratt, Kieran Culkin, Emma Stone, Richard Gere, Kate Bosworth, Liev Schreiber, Naomi Watts, Justin Long, Uma Thurman, Jason Sudeikis, Kristen Bell, Bobby Cannavale, Christopher Mintz-Plasse, Chloe Grace Moretz, Gerard Butler, Seann William Scott, Terrence Howard and others doing and saying things you may NEVER have thought you'd see on film!  Indeed, if you gross out easily or are easily offended, this for sure is NOT the film for you.  Conversely, if you have an open mind and a sense of humor that sometimes lends to the bizarre, some of the shorts in this film are laugh-out-loud funny, and worth wading through some of the lamer segments to get to.  Not everything works here, by any means, but enough does to make it worth watching.  Just be forewarned - the humor here is VERY adult (in content; in maturity level it sometimes sinks to "neanderthal" for sure), and VERY bizarre.  But again, even as you gasp at some of the more shocking moments, you may also find yourself laughing like hell over some of them.

O or South Park is stupid and of no comedic value, skip this; you'll likely find it as worthless as so many of the professional critics.

However, if you know what you're getting into, which is a series of completely unrelated short comedies, with revolting and ridiculous themes, then it may be worth a watch. I did laugh far more than I thought I would.

One of the earlier skits consists of two people on a blind date, one of whom has a scrotum hanging from his neck, but appears to be unaware of it.

This movie is not Saving Private Ryan. It isn't Titanic or Lincoln. It is low-brow comedy trash. But it's good low-brow comedy trash.
Overall it was a terrible movie but it did have a few funny parts if you like over the top random comedy.
My husband wanted me to rate it a 5 but there was just one skit I didn't like. We laughed the whole time.
I can't believe so many celebrities participated in this sick flick. Don't waste your money. I did. I wish I could get mine back.
I will forever check reviews before watching a movie from this point forward... This movie has been a huge waste of time!

The previews lied and made this movie look interesting, a little irreverent, and funny.  There were funny parts but they were SO NOT worth the rest of the time spent watching this crap.

Do yourself a favor and skip it!

Great low brow humor. As enjoyable as "Kentucky Fried Movie" if you enjoy that style of humor. I had some great laughs at the immature humor, sarcasm and obnoxious skits. The "Truth or Dare" skit was very funny. Although I have to say, It is definitely not for everyone.

We rented this because we thought the previews were hilarious.  We also thought that there so many big names in it, that it could not be bad... well, we were wrong. This movie was horrible. I have never wanted to stop a movie foe being so bad before. It is disgusting, and not even funny disgusting, but I think I may vomit gross instead. I wish there was a way to get a refund on a digital purchase because $4 was $4 too much.
All the funny parts were shown on the preview. I would pass on this unless you want to be disappointed during most of the movie.

If you are ready for a laugh, I recommend this movie.  Sick, yes, but this is the funniest movie... ever.  I have since watched some of the other "sketch" type movies reviewers mentioned, and they aren't as good.  I saw Movie 43 on the big screen and laughed all the way through... couldn't stop laughing... think I annoyed some people there, but I don't get out much, and have too much stress, and really needed a laugh.  It was awesome.  A month ago I watched the trailer and laughed.  Can't wait to get the DVD and see it again!
I didn't find a single thing funny or entertaining about this movie, I wish I had read the reviews before renting it. This movie is not worth paying for, or even watching for free

I am a BIG fan of the Farrelly Bros, e.g., Hall Pass, Three Stooges, Heartbreak Kid, There's Something About Mary, Dumb & Dumber, yet there is something very odd and inexplicable when this very unfunny script calls for audience members to witness a young girl's menses, mommy incest, bullying, intolerance, arbitrary violence, and brutality in the name of comedy. If there are any redeeming qualities to this film, then I don't see them. Movie 43 would not even make it to or be included in the "it is so bad, it is good" category. A bad acid trip or men/women gone wild. This is nothing more than a disgusting, offensive, and poorly edited movie.

It was horrible. It was nothing but crass and raunch. Not even humorous raunchiness, just straight up, lets see how disgusting and stupid I can be. I only paid 4 dollars to see it...that was too much!!!!! Don't waste your time, I know the cast looks bad ass, but it sucked beyond words.
this is the most worthless movie ever created (IMHO) and I suggest that you stay away and do not spend your money

The film "Movie 43" was honestly one of the most over hyped, over produced, worthless films that I have ever seen. The plot line is all over the place, and it seems as if the script was written by a 12 year old. The only entertaining portion involved "speed dating", and even then that segment like all others in the film dragged out for far too long. I had never considered walking out of a theater after paying until I saw this film. It was not worth my money in the theaters, and I would never suggest this to someone unless they were only paying 99 cents and were bedridden due illness or surgery. Final Grade: D-

For those that are familiar with the Jamie Kennedy documentary titled "heckler", I would incredibly enjoy to have the opportunity he gave to an online critic. To get the chance to sit down with any number of the actors in this film and let them know that staplers are funnier than they were. This would be the only justice for such a disaster of a Hollywood investment and consumption of my time.
Judging by the rave reviews (positive as well as negative), I know it's my kind of movie, bring on the rude humor and fart jokes!!!

I didn't go into this movie thinking I was going to pee my pants laughing for every second of the movie. Maybe that's where the problem with the negative reviews lies. Like most comedy films, there are parts that are hilarious and there are parts that aren't. I read one review that said the "only" funny part of the movie was a part that neither my husband or I laughed at. Humor is relative, and I know that my husband and I giggled, at the minimum, for MOST of this movie. There were two or three skits that weren't all that funny, but I didn't leave the movie thinking it was the worst movie ever - which is what some of these reviews say. Lots of dick and fart jokes... this is not intellectual humor, or even dark humor. It's slapstick and dumb, but that's funny to some people. Definitely made my husband and I laugh til our faces were red. I'm glad I ignored the reviews.
The only skit that was funny was the superhero speed dating skit. Jason Sudekis is hilarious! But that's one out of ten. Four thumbs down! Boo.
The best parts were in the previews. The rest of the movie was a complete waste of time. I hope this company lost lots of money producing it.
Great cast and absolutely ridiculous movie. Exactly what I wanted to watch. Exactly what I expected. Don't forget to watch all the way past the credits. I laughed so hard the neighbors came over
Both me and the hubby enjoyed this movie, just a warning! There is no plot: it was a compling of short skits like SNL
DON'T DO IT!! Trust me. Save you money. This was a total time suck! Honestly, there were only a few points that resembled humor, and those were few and far between.
I promise this is the worst movie ever. they don't even try to see the premise thru. I laughed twice. watch clips on you tube. guarantee if you think this is funny you're an idiot

Do not in any way fall for the trailer with all the A+++ lister actors. This is nearly unwatchable. No, for me it is unwatchable because I turned it off after 20 minutes.  Unfunnily gross script and scenes, embarrassing situations. And worse of all it is just not funny.  I winced after watching Naomi Watts make a pass at the actor who played her teen son. Its one thing to deal with horrible situations on film, its totally another to pass that off as comedy. Ugh.

Never again will I pay for a movie and then read the Rotten Tomato reviews.

This movie was basically a bunch of weird shorts that weren't really funny. I gave it a shot because the cast made it seam as if it could be funny even if it was a bit dumb but it was neither funny nor entertaining
boring, not funny, what more can i say do not waste your time. They did not even get me to laugh not once
This movie was kind of a joke!  I believe they were trying to hard to make this movie funny.  Would've been okay without a lot of parts.

This movie i rented was actually pretty funny. There really isn't a story line but many various skits throughout the movie. Kind of like a snl movie. They do take extremes in the movie, but if you can get the humor, then its pretty funny.

Some films are so bad you want to see them for the spectacle. Not this one.

Somehow they managed to use a variety of stars who not only make a tedious, boring and uninteresting movie, but one that is not even bad enough to see just out of curiosity.

I laughed once. Briefly. At a fake commercial claiming vending machines had crying children inside them. This faint glimmer of humor was quickly overwhelmed by the depression brought on by the movie not ending.

Imagine a variety of stars reading lines they hope will shock you into laughing. The shock is lame and any other reason to laugh is absent. You don't even feel sorry for the actors, who seem sincere in their desire to make a good movie, but come off as having no sense of humor whatsoever.

The best thing about this movie is the argument it makes for a refund policy for boring you to death.

The only comfort you find in this movie is that you recognize the actors... And they too must be grimacing after viewing.
I understand the statement being made within the movie...... I believe the statement is that Hollywood makes a lot of crap movies as if someone must have been holding a gun to their head.
so the only positive thing I can say about this movie Is that, yes, they made their point, ..... But it just wasn't funny enough or entertaining enough to support the statement.  Unfortunate.

This is the first time I've ever written a review on Amazon because I decided it was important to let the masses know what a pile of garbage this movie is. I'm so upset with myself that I just wasted money purchasing and time watching that horse crap movie.

I read some of the mixed reviews here and I have to say that all the low ranked ones are right on the money!  I mean I saw the trailer and it looked like it was going to be a fun movie and I read some of the reviews and decided to take a change on it, but oh my gosh... this must seriously be the worst moive ever made!!!  Absolutely not worth buying and I wouldn't even pay to rent it.. wait for netflix or for when it becomes available to view for free if you are an amazon prime member.

I should have looked at the reviews before watching this one. The trailer looked funny, lots of actors which would lead you to believe it would be a good film -wrong.
Cheesy, bad humor, some scenes a rather disturbing.
Hard to imagine how actors such as Dennis Quaid, Seth MacFarlane, Hugh Jackman, Kate Winslet, and many others signed on to such a badly written film.
A total waste of time.

I really loved this movie and can't wait until it's out on DVD. I've never laughed out loud so hard in a movie before. Everything was so unexpected. I thought it was hilarious and can't believe it didn't gross more in the theaters.
Complete waste of money! Should have listened to previous reviews... This is a perfect example of how a well-edited trailer can go a long way.
Movie 43 is the craziest movie i have watched thus far. Not for the whole family but a funny movie.
Wasn't to fond of this movie! Even with all it's big actors in it I would not watch again at all!!!

This movie is not good. It is not funny. The awesome stable of actors were reportedly guilted into their parts. It was like watching an ill-conceived version of a live-action Adult Swim short. It was also very short, like 65 minutes, still probably too long. Crude jokes and no real story made it near unwatchable. I was very excited for this, my fianc nearly killed me when I vetoed to see this instead of her movie choice. She was right to be so upset.

While this movie may not be for older conservative audiences, I laughed a lot! I think this movie was directly intended for a younger audience such as college students. I laughed through the whole movie and it gave me a lot of shock and awe value. If you like crude humor and don't mind sexual innuendos then try this movie out. I am so glad I did!
This movie is simply horrible and a complete waste of time. If I could give no stars I would have.

Movie 43 is very underrated, while not every skit was laugh out loud funny (the first one comes to mind), several were.

The movie is also not just dumb comedy, several of the skits poke fun at social topics relevant today (overbearing parents obsessed with having perfect kids as an example).  And some of them are just purely for fun.  If you don't like or can't chuckle at potty humor, you may not like the show.  But it is absolutely underrated.

What were all of these great actors thinking about making the worst movie ever made!  This movie wasted $12.99 of my hard earned money, I wish I never saw this movie.  Please save your time and money and do not watch this movie.

This was definitely a pleasant surprise based on all of the previous reviews, most of them negative. I think people were going into it not knowing what they were getting into. This should win awards based on originality. The superhero and leprechaun stories were hilarious. Well done!
Not even worth watching the first 10 minutes. I like quirky, off beat movies but this one was just boring. Couple of semi funny scenes but don't spend money on this!

I can handle shock comedy, in fact I invite it, but there was nothing clever about anything remotely involved in this film. It lacked direction, the jokes were just plain dumb, calling them childish would almost be a compliment. Generally, I can find something I like about most movies no matter how awful they are, this film just falls extremely flat. Save your money and your dignity, watch something else.

This movie is not funny. This is just a poor attempt at appealing to the most base type of humor. It's all testicle and poop jokes, and not even funny ones. Filthy jokes can be funny, but they still have to be jokes. You can't just show balls and poop on screen and expect people to laugh. Worse than Bruno.

For the record, I'm not a prude. If this movie was full of dirty jokes that actually made me laugh, I would be rating it five stars. This was complete garbage, not even funny.
Wrong on so many levels but it felt so right. I was laughing so hard I had tears. I don't care what anyone says this movie is one that will be watched often.
It has been a long time since I laughed like that. Great movie and the cast is just outstanding. On the line with some issues, but never over it.
Terrible let down, has one, maybe two funny sketches but thats it, if you want to see the funniest version of the film, watch the red band trailer, thats really all the best parts of the film.

I think this movie has something for everyone. I began hating it and almost stopped watching several times but --I've just finished -- and somehow have the desire to own it as part of my collection. The skits are too short, I feel like there's a lot of missed opportunities that were cut because of the robot chicken nature of the film. But like I said, there are a few parts that are just awkward to sit through but there were a few times where I could not help but laugh out loud, something I don't often do. It will probably offend all women and small children...and really you have to be a young adult 20-30 to really hit the sweet spot they were targeting.
some skits were really funny and interesting takes on our society and some not so much.  worth a $3.99 rental.  not worth buying.

I liked the way this movie was set up, but I like the short sketches. When I was younger I would watch IFC constantly just to catch a nice independent short film. I'm not sure if they still show them since I do not have time to watch the boob-tube much, but this movie reminded me of the same type of shorts they would show. I do not think this movie deserves 5 stars, but it does not deserve one star either. I would give it a solid 3. If you have the right sense of humor, you will dig this movie. If you are offended by it, then I guess that sucks for you. I enjoyed most of it. Some of it sucked though. I didn't pay to watch this movie, so I'm not bitter at all. The internet is very useful when it comes to watching movies streaming for free. One last thing... I laughed pretty hard when I read the review talking about the American Pie movies. Give me a break! Those movies are terrible! I was in high school when the first one came out. It seemed like the only people who thought they were great were the d-bags who acted like Stiffler after they watched it.
Terrible. Do not waste your time, money, or dignity. I wish I could unsee this. I am upset I am forced to give it even 1 star.

the only funny part is where the children are stuck in the copier. everything else is garbage. believe me, I have a sick, dark sense of humor and found this movie to be just awful. it was embarrassing to be part of the audience and be partaking in this garbage. please, life is too short. watch something else

Oh, what a hilarious beginning. Then it got slightly disturbing. All in the name of laughs though.
An all-star studded cast keeps you watching for more, no matter the depth of the disturbance.
Dennis Quaid is a riot!!!
Love the Super Hero skit best. OMG too funny! So many heroes, and so much fun!
This is definitely not a movie you watch with your kids. Number one it's too disturbing in parts for kids, and two, they won't get the jokes anyways. An adult movie all the way!
The bloopers at the end are funny too and worth watching, but the short was once again disturbingly funny.

"This video is so illegal that it has been banned by every country in the world, including Amsterdam." After an older brother and his friend are pranked by his younger brother they come up with one of their own for payback. What starts off as a joke quickly balloons out of control into something that can destroy the world. There really isn't much to say about this. It is more of a series of vignette's staring some of Hollywood's most famous doing the weirdest and grossest things you can think of. Think to yourself what is one thing I thought I'd never see in a movie...it's probably in here. Personally I thought the movie was very funny and watching with the right group of people would make it even better, but be warned...it is extremely offensive! If you think you may get offended then by all means avoid this. If you have a wide sense of humor and are looking for something to just watch and not have to think about then this movie is for you. Overall, I thought it was funny but be prepared for what you are about to experience. I give it a B.

This movie was never going to be an Oscar contender but...If you like Dark humor and are not afraid to laugh at a few Non-PC moments, this is for you.  Yes, some of the skits could have been better but a few really hit it out of the dirty humor park.  Get some adult beverages and a few friends (with the same humor as you) and make a night out of it.
If you're going to be offensive, at least write funny material. Being offensive purely to be offensive is not funny. Stay away from this movie.

this review is on the blu ray disc of the movie-
movie - 4 / 5
video - 4.5 / 5
audio - 4 / 5
funny and raunchy stories rolled together in one good movie.
A must see. Ill watch it again and again.the funniest movie of the year by far. Not for the kids but the part entiled homeschooling is the best

I'm a huuuge movie fan of all genres and this one is among the worst.  It's not even "fun-bad."  This is the only review I've ever written here -- but I wanted to take a few moments to warn others that this is pure garbage.  They should pay us to watch it, not the other way around.
nearly had to walk out of the theatre it was so bad, had some funny moments, but over all my top worst movie ever

My girlfriend and I actually saw this "film" at the movies during his regular theatrical release period.  It is the worst movie I have ever seen, bar none.

It just is stupid, a waste of talented actors, and needed a real script.

As a Blu-Ray only buyer, I see no need for anything in this movie that would even require Blu-Ray quality.  It should have been released only in Beta format, if it had to be released at all

I went to see this after not having heard or read anything about the movie.  Looking at the cast I was expecting a masterpiece.  I have a very high level of respect for most of the cast members and their acting\comic abilities but this movie just missed the mark.  There were a few chuckles, and I AM a fan of vulgar comedies ,.... they do not offend me in the least. That being said it was like a bad season of SNL.  They would take a premise or a one-liner and completely hammer all the funny out of it.  If I had not been waiting for my wife and daughter to come out of another theater I would have walked out of this movie ,.... it was that bad,....and I NEVER walk out of movies. As I said VERY talented cast but this effort just was not funny to me.

This is a seriously underrated and unappreciated comedy containing about fifteen comedic shorts. It's at times mean-spirited and disgusting, but all in good fun and humor. The actors are clearly having a great time, and most of them really go with the outrageous material given to them. If you want to spend a solid 90 minutes one night, Movie 43 is an excellent choice and one hell of a film.

To keep it simple this is basically a waste of your money. It's not worth a dollar let alone the $21 or $28 they want you to pay. I might have barely chuckled once or twice during the whole thing. And my opinion of the famous and highly talented actors who involved themselves in this project almost makes me want to boycott anything they ever do again. If I could I would give it a negative rating. Again, PLEASE save your money!!!!

Saw this film twice and will pick it up on Blu Ray!

Subversive, creative, original, refreshing, funny! - This list of adjectives could go on! - Simply put, Watch it!!

My advice - Don't be a sheep like all the critics! Open your mind! Movie 43 is the most original film Hollywood has produced in a very long time! It's a film like this that weeds out the prudish, conservative, stuck-up/elitist nay-sayers!

My only wish is Hollywood produces more films like this (And no i'm talking about generic 'Scary Movie' or 'Disaster Movie' spoof films) - (This film is much more creative and subversive than those films)

Very funny film from start to finish, I can understand why this is not for everyone, its very vulgar throughout with some really ballsy off the wall humour that will offend people, but if you love movies like Amazon women on the moon and the onion movie then you will certainly enjoy this, I don't understand the negativity the theatre was in hysterics when I saw this, very bold and original with an all star cast making fools of themselves, brilliant!!! I hope there's more of these.

This movie had me in awe.  How did this get made?  The writing is well beyond lazy and filled with gags that only a 10 year old could enjoy.  SPOILERS!  One of the first sketches involves Hugh Jackman having a scrotum hanging from his neck.  It only gets worse from there.  Need I say more?

This is the "Kentucky Fried Movie" or "Groove Tube" for this generation. Normally this type of crude humor is done by unknowns looking to start a career and not by Hollywood's elite looking to end their career. There are numerous skits, most of which concern sex in one way or another. Some are cruder than others, some are out right funny while others you might find disgusting.

If you are turned off by crude humor, you should avoid this film. However, if you love the crude humor of modern films, this one will keep you in stitches.

Parental Guide: F-bomb and nudity.
I laughed from beginning to end! You must be able to take a joke about sensitive things. If you can't, don't watch it. I loved loved loved it!!1
Love this movie and I know that makes me a special breed of human....don't care, it's one of my guilty pleasures and it ALWAYS make me laugh
If you thought "Not Another Teen Movie" was funny then you will love this one
Very stupid move not funny at all

It started off really strong. The Hugh Jackman blind date sketch and the home school sketch had me in stitches. However, the rest of the sketches were just okay, and the in-between story was really weak.
Messed up but rrally funny movie.

NOT for old people with a dead sense of humor. If you cant take a joke and get sand in the Vag1n/\ then don't get it. Its harmless and such simple madness. Rent first and you will know in the first 10 mins if its a keeper.
HILARIOUS
Not for the squeamish, but pee your pants and "no she didn't just say that" kind of funny!!!
So funny
Absolutely terrible movie. We rented it because of the lineup of actors, this was such a waste of time we did not bother to finish it.
